The area of a parallelogram formed by two vectors \(\mathbf{u}\) and \(\mathbf{v}\) can be found using the magnitude of their cross product. The formula is given by: \[ \text{Area} = \| \mathbf{u} \times \mathbf{v} \| \] where \(\mathbf{u} \times \mathbf{v}\) is the cross product of the vectors \(\mathbf{u}\) and \(\mathbf{v}\). For the vectors \(\mathbf{u} = \begin{pmatrix} 3 \\ 1 \\ -2 \end{pmatrix}\) and \(\mathbf{v} = \begin{pmatrix} 1 \\ -3 \\ 4 \end{pmatrix}\), the cross product is computed as: \[
\mathbf{u} \times \mathbf{v} = \begin{vmatrix} \mathbf{i} & \mathbf{j} & \mathbf{k} \\ 3 & 1 & -2 \\ 1 & -3 & 4 \end{vmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} (1 \cdot 4) - (-2 \cdot -3) \\ -((3 \cdot 4) - (-2 \cdot 1)) \\ (3 \cdot -3) - (1 \cdot 1) \end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} 4 - 6 \\ -(12 + 2) \\ -9 - 1 \end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} -2 \\ -14 \\ -10 \end{pmatrix}
\] The magnitude of this cross product is given by: \[
\| \mathbf{u} \times \mathbf{v} \| = \sqrt{(-2)^2 + (-14)^2 + (-10)^2} = \sqrt{4 + 196 + 100} = \sqrt{300} = 10\sqrt{3}
\] The area of the parallelogram is therefore \(\boxed{10\sqrt{3}}\). </think> <answer>10\sqrt{3}\end{answer}

